@JG_Nuke The 2Y Treasury selloff amid a “risk-on” rally suggests traders are repricing near-term inflation or supply risk, not celebrating growth. The tariff pause wasn’t a true de-escalation it was selective (excluding China), and likely seen as a political maneuver, not a reflationary catalyst.

Meanwhile, gold ripping +$100 in tandem with risk assets implies safe haven demand is still active. That’s a red flag. It tells us this “euphoria” is hedged, fragmented, and uncertain not broad conviction. Add in swap spread collapse, funding stress, and bond auction weakness earlier in the day, and the moves look more like desperate positioning adjustments than true macro relief.

You’re right something doesn’t add up, and it’s because under the hood, nothing was actually fixed.

